76561197979959418,Recommended,221260,26920961,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Waveform,"Little Inferno is a charming one.If you had any previous experience with World of Goo, you should know exactly what to expect out of this little piece's flavor and aesthetics. For many small games, there is a point where, for the sake of keeping up with the challenges the gameplay introduces, the player's mind effectively strips away the colorful facade of it, revealing the core mechanics to be yet another twist on an ages old arcade, which it is perceived as from there on. Here, that's hardly the case.Then again, the complexity of Little Inferno's gameplay is somewhere between that of Clicker Heroes and a bubble wrap simulator. Yet, given how deeply satisfying the look and feel of this trivial process proves, and how the occasional story shards keep popping up at just the right moments, this simplicity manages to give birth to some mesmerizing immersion.The visuals are freakishly grotesque and disarmingly adorable at the same time, and the beautiful soundtrack contributes overwhelming emotionality to the process. Invest in it just a bit, click away the build-up, and you find yourself at the story's climax, gasping for every little final detail like a revelation.Little Inferno is a cozy place to be. The flames will consume you whole. But that's okay."
