,Recommended,221260,8815473,"Posted: 22 January, 2014",all,Sasquash,"In Little Inferno, you sit in front of a fireplace and burn everything. It is absolutely brilliant. Before the brilliance, however, a few words of warning to the wary buyer. There's a fair amount of waiting in the game, and the puzzles you complete to progress are by no means difficult. If this does not trouble you at all, then stop reading this review right now and buy the game.For those who remain, I present some positives. Little Inferno isn't the most technologically advanced software ever, but it looks very pretty. The bright fire effects and ""JUST BURN EVERYTHING"" gameplay will satisfy your inner child and pyromaniac alike. The things you're burning are quite entertaining in themselves. The game gives each a humorous name and description, and each reacts to being set on fire in a different way. An alarm clock rings until its untimely demise, a model bank churns out money, and firecrackers do exactly what you think they'd do.So, LIttle Inferno is a solid fireplace simulator. But is that it? Is it worth $10? Go watch the trailer, and think about it. There is most definitely something more. As you start up the game, Kyle Gabler's incredible soundtrack dares you to say otherwise. And that is exactly everything I can say about that without ruining it.tl;drLittle Inferno is great. There's fires, and a bunch of other really great stuff that you need to play to find out for yourself, so go buy it. Also, the soundtrack is amazing."
