,Recommended,221260,8918413,"Posted: 30 January, 2014",all,XiaoXiaoMan,"I'd like to start by saying if there were a ""Mixed"" option, I'd pick that for my recommendation.I can't say I can really call this a good game so much as I call it a fun toy. The fire physics are fun to play with, and this game is guaranteed to make the pyromaniac inside you cackle with glee as you burn stuff. Some items are fun just to play with instead of just burn right away (Manly Razer comes to mind). A lot of the things react in unique ways when burned, others... do nothing at all. But if you ever wanted to burn an opera lady or a pirate or... well, this is the place to do it. In that regard, Little Inferno is fun. Some people will say that's enough. It's made more appealing by the story that goes along with it, told through the letters you receive from three different people. While I kinda like the story itself, some of the themes lose their impact due to their overly repetitive nature. I invite you to take a shot every time someone mentions something not lasting forever or never being able to go back.Another thing I don't really understand is why after buying something, you have to wait for it to ship to you. Some items take a few seconds, others take a couple minutes (I believe the longest you'll wait for an item is five minutes). So if you run out of stuff to burn and are waiting for your next batch to arrive, the gameplay grinds to a halt, leaving you sitting there like a putz while you wait for your stuff. If you happen to get some Tomorrow Bucks, you can use those to skip the shipping time, but the game is very stingy about handing them out. The best way to get more is by finding combos, which is also required to unlock the other catalogs. Oh, and did I mention after buying something, not only does it take a while for it to ship to you, but it takes even longer to restock?So to some degree, it feels like I'm playing a free to play game where if I don't have or don't want to spend money (or Tomorrow Bucks in this case), I have to wait to keep playing. I'm not convinced that's a good choice of gameplay mechanic. At least it isn't riddled with microtransactions like free to play games.I wouldn't say Little Inferno is bad, but my biggest gripe is the waiting system; it's just an unnecessary feature that gets in the way of what's otherwise a fun little experience. You'll have an enjoyable time when you're not waiting for more things to burn. I think the story is the strongest point of the game, even though themes are repeated to the point of losing most of their impact.You're more than likely to play this game, finish the story, maybe mess around with burning stuff for a little while, and then get bored and uninstall it. Worth checking out, but I suggest you wait for a sale; this fun toy of a game isn't worth full price."
