76561198002174953,Recommended,221260,14475109,"Posted: 14 February, 2015",all,Auraion,"Little inferno.It looks quite simple and superficial at first with the old fashioned catchy jingle and the sing-a-long lyrics...But after spending some time playing it starts to creep up on you. At first its like yay! Who are these people writing to me? Woo! I get to play with fire! and you spend your time methodically setting the acheivement list alight one combo at a time, sending things to Sugar Plumps and listening to the weather reports.Until you start to think... I'm burning my toys. Why?Why is it so cold? Why is there no sun?And the game takes a depressing sort of turn as something happens to your neighbour and then all of a sudden you too find yourself cast out and upon seeing the world outside you realise things about yourself and the state of your own reality that will honestly make you cry. This game is a briliant sneaking satirical look at casting off the things of our childhood and that which distracts us and makes us realise that there is more to life than what we've been doing all this time. Dreams can come true when we stop getting distracted and try that little bit harder.I'd recomend playing this game simply because of the feels it invokes as you play and I would congratulate the devs on such a thoughtful couple of hours that honestly could change a life."
