,Not Recommended,221260,8156752,"Posted: 20 December, 2013",all,Shadowspaz,"This does not mean I did not enjoy the game- I greatly enjoyed it. But I cannot recommend this game to anyone I do not know: It is a very specific taste of game.This will not appeal to the average gamer. If you are looking for depth, you may enjoy it. If you are looking for a great gameplay experience, you likely won't. If you just want to burn everything, you'll love it. The gameplay is built around repetition and waiting, as a satire of AVGM and the pay-to-win formula used in Facebook games. But this means that the game is designed to be repetitive: Not a great trait in most games. And if you don't like waiting five minutes to burn a single thing, it'll cost you stamps, which are an in-game currency you slowly accumulate.The entire game takes place in front of a fireplace, with the exception of the end, which serves to teach a preachy lesson about wasted time. But there is more to it than that, if you're willing to look into it. The depth is a decent hook for game analysts, and the meaning of the ending is vague enough to be interpreted as a good number of things, all positive and optimistic. Most people won't look into this, though, and I don't blame them.The atmosphere is just as fantastic and eerie as World of Goo was (Same creator), with that silver lining lingering in the distance. The dialogue is kooky and fun, yet reveals a dark and sinister motive. But I expect most gamers' reactions to this would be ""so what?"" Atmosphere does not make the game. It cannot serve as the initial hook, and only becomes tangible when the player is immersed.So no, I don't recommend it. It has fantastic atmosphere. It has a dark theme. It has a sweet-but-simple ending. It has great idle gameplay. But you would need to be an ""artistic"" gamer to acknowledge most of this. If you don't look for atmosphere in games, you won't care about it in this one. If you play games to play games, this falls short of the criteria.However, my negative rating of this will likely draw people that are honestly researching into if they should get this game. And, as you read through my review, you may notice that I am not describing you. You may think ""I'm not an average gamer. These assumptions don't apply to me."" If that's the case, then enjoy Little Inferno, as I have."
