76561198039364415,Not Recommended,221260,10024803,"Posted: 5 May, 2014",all,Arpwnian,"What can be said about Little Inferno... well, popular websites have glorified it as the second-coming of indie games.  I bought the game because I was bored and burning things sounded entertaining (literally, that was all there was to the purchase).  I saw all the tags by gaming journalists that claimed it was a thought-provoking look into the demons of modern society... but I ignored them.  After playing it for a while I asked myself… were they right?  Is Little Inferno the reincarnated savior of gaming?  The answer is complicated, and as a disclaimer let me say that Little Inferno is a very player-driven experience; to some it will speak volumes, to others it will fall far short of the mark.I must admit that I haven't beaten the game; the tear-jerker of an ending has eluded me thus far.  Why haven't I beaten it, you ask?  To put it bluntly, the game isn't all that engaging.  Burning things is cool for a while, and hunting down the combinations of items to receive bonus points is amusing… but it doesn’t last.  Receiving letters from my neighbors and the weatherman – things that are supposed to be thought-provoking and emotional - get bogged down by the overly-satirical feel of the game.In the same way that some game worlds are grimdark to be grimdark, Little Inferno's world is dystopian to be dystopian.  The game is out to prove that we, as modern humans, sacrifice things like emotion and human contact for happiness – and it attempts to do so in a great, sweeping motion that’s supposed to knock our socks off.  I, personally, wasn’t impressed... though on this rare occasion I will tell you to draw your own conclusions."
