,Recommended,221260,17028953,"Posted: 13 July, 2015",all,slimbuttons,"Burned things.Found freedom.11/10if you've heard all about this game: it's as good as you've heard, you should get it and play it.if not, ditto the second part.whatLittle Infernodoes is skewer the ""Farmville etc."" business model of games that monetize on all of our need to have some casual game in our hands, our dependence on the screens that we carry everywhere, and most of all our willingness to pay real money to accelerate silly resource-farming in-game stuff that really is just an endless cycle of... whatever, more in-game stuff.except the skewering is wrapped in areally fungame of that type: all you do in this game (till the very end) is throw stuff that you buy into a fireplace in various combinations, and burn the stuff; burning stuff gets you more coins to buy more stuff, and throwing in combinations unlocks new catalogues of stuff, etc. (see how it's satire?) But that action is pretty fun: the fireplace is fun, the combo-searching is fun, thesnap-crackle-POPas things go up in flames is very fun.then all of this is interlaced with an emerging narrative that pretty much just sheds light on what's clear from the start--that ""something is very wrong here""; that this thing that you're just sitting there staring it isn't really making you happy or healthy. While that's not surprising, the narrative is very engagingly and tensely teased out, so that I found myself playing long after I was tired and the fun-action of throwing stuff into the fireplace had lost some of its luster, because I was really invested in the story. Which has, thankfully, an elegant and optimistic conclusion.Lastly, the music is terrific; deliberately evocative and sweeping and terrific.It's a great game that's a commentary on gaming and a great game in its own right. The whole thing will take you like 1/15th of the time you'll spend in a big AAA game, and you might get more out of it."
