,Recommended,221260,16710901,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Lowbacca1977,"Little Inferno is a great game, but it's important to know what it is. On the simplest level, it's simply burning things in a fireplace. What impresses me so much with this is that the physics of burning stuff is done quite well, and there's something satisfying just watching stuff burn (as there should be) and that alone was fun to play with for a while.The next level is the combo system, whereby you get some extra perks by burning certain objects together. For the most part, these can be figured out with a bit of thinking, although there's a few of them that I think are not 'good' solutions. Or at least, I think there's more sensible solutions to it. There's 99 combos, and I'd say about 2/3rds can be gotten relatively easily, but the last few can be really tricky.On the final level, there's a sort of plot-based undercurrent in here that I think is really interesting initially, but ultimately unsatisfying. It is sorta similar to how World of Goo had a similar plot that is introduced very subtly. I really wish that the plot had been a bit more fleshed out, I get hints of a larger message it was meant to lead to, but it feels indecisive about it.Overall, the game's a fun 4-5 hours and I think there's a good sense of humour to it. There's some forced waiting in the game that I think could've been reduced so that late game was less tedious at points (particularly when trying to figure out combos). That said, unlike World of Goo, there really isn't replay value, unless you enjoy watching the fire. There's nothing to go back and try to earn once you have figured out all the combos so I do think it's important to know that buying this game is buying a 4-5 hour experience and not much more than that."
