76561198037165915,Recommended,221260,14635382,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,PiperUSA,"""Little Inferno"" is a wonderfully made game that features a simple storyline, and game mechanics that are fun even after you finish the game. With a game that takes place (almost) entirely in front of a fireplace it is a all aroung brilliant game for its price and the amount of computer space it takes up.Pros And ConsPros-Can be ran on toasters, (older computers)-Wonderful Graphics and Mechanics-Simple Easy to understand storyline, yet still enjoyableCons-Can be spoiled easilly, DO NOT watch videos on gameplay unless you want it spoiled-I can be hard to get to late game without guides on combos, so prepare for a long game if your not using guides.-Oh my gosh, MISS NANCY"
76561198031398133,Recommended,221260,23851005,"Posted: 26 June, 2016",all,Kadera,"""Little Inferno"" has been out for a few years now, but I only just encountered it as part of the Steam 2016 summer sale. It's quirky, weird, and oddly engrossing. You're a kid with not much, but you do have a magic fireplace and a directive to burn stuff because it's apparently been snowing forever outside. Everything given to you can (and should) be set on fire, and fortunately you can do this just by pointing at it (holding down controller or mouse button as appropriate).I'll be honest and admit it was the two preview videos on the Steam store page which caused me to have to buy the game. I just couldn't not. It's like being inside an episode of Ren & Stimpy.As you burn stuff, it produces coins which you can then use to purchase more items to burn, and as you buy more items, it unlocks more catalogs of stuff to buy. (Bit of a consumerism message in there, I should think.) The only real challenge sometimes is figuring out all of the various combinations of items which, when burned together, produce bonuses and little achievement messages. (I'll give you one obvious combo: Pirate toy + boat.)  At times, you receive letters from people -- Miss Nancy, who apparently runs the Little Inferno program. A girl in the same predicament as you. And a weather guy in a balloon. (Yes, you burn their letters, too.)After you've burned everything you can burn... well, let's just say the ending is pretty good. Not so sure the game is worth the original list price unless you have more than one person in your household, but it is absolutely worth the price when on sale. At least I thought so."
