,Recommended,221260,849718,"Posted: 2 December, 2012",all,Jerakal,"I knew I was going to love this game right out the gate. Made by the same company that made World of Good, The Tomorrow Corporation, I knew I could expect a few things from this game:-An eerie but endearing artstyle.-A more than mildly distressing distressing story.And of course, absolute insanity.I can safely say that it disappointed in none of these respects. In this game, the main character is a child, burning toys and other objects in a fireplace to stay warm through a mysterious and never-ending winter. Burning items gives you currency and unlocks more things to burn, allowing you to gradually unlock more things to play with as well as more of the story.Items burn in unique and often realistic ways, and the game give the player enough item variety and space to work with to keep this fresh for several hours, just long enough to see the story through to it's conclusion.My only gripe with the game lies in the item cooldowns and delivery times, which seem to be nothing more than a tool to extend the gametime due to an overall lack of content. There is a system in place to combat this, in the form of stamps awarded for solving rather simple puzzles involving burning specific combinations of items, but I didn't really feel that it added much to the game.The character dialogue and the design of the multitude of burnable items in the game are absolutely charming all the way through. I certainly enjoyed Little Inferno while it lasted, but it's hard to say whether or not it was quite worth the $15 pricetag.I'll just say that if a game where you haphazardly order items out of a catalogue only to shovel them into a firepit and see how well they immolate together sound like fun, you may want to give Little Inferno a look. (Though you may want to wait for it to go on sale.)"
,Recommended,221260,11709361,"Posted: 14 August, 2014",all,adamrocz,"This was a great game.It wasn't just the gameplay. The story was awesome (with a hint of dystopia), the art was great and the music was nice as well. Altogether a good game that shouldn't take more than four hours to play the first time, though you'll probably play it again."
