,Recommended,221260,11081721,"Posted: 5 July, 2014",all,Centaura,"I rarely write reviews, but I just completed Little Inferno and feel...overwhelmed and excited! I first saw this game played on YouTube and I bought it thinking it would be a neat little time-consumer. Was I ever wrong! Little Inferno is much more than just burning stuff and watching the flames flicker out. There is a depth here you wouldn't expect at first glance. It's a short game (I completed it in just over 7 hours, but I also spent a lot of time distracted, and making sure I got all 99 combos, some of which are a little...vague), and yet it ends on a high note that made my heart swell at 5 in the morning.The graphics are a little bit Tim Burton; unique, peculiar, and that sort of creepy-cute; the fire effect is realistic and oddly comforting. The music is fantastic andemotional, when it picks up you reallyfeelit; it's not just background noise. Gameplay is pretty standard and easy to grasp (click-and-drag, mostly), and the only thing really holding you back are the combos, which are mostly obvious - the more vague ones feel rather satisfying to complete.If you want a rather quick game that's fun to play, easy to understand, and surprisingly multi-faceted and emotional - buy Little Inferno."
