,Recommended,221260,7392225,"Posted: 15 October, 2013",all,Julian Sark,"Found this by accident during the weekly sales.If anyone should wonder if games can be art, well, in my view, this is.It sure isn't the greatest game ever (even though the artwork and music is all extremely nice and burning the items is fun), maybe its not even truly a game. It's not long, it's not  replayable in a ""finding something new"" sense.But then, its so much more than this. Its a message, it's emotional. I can not disclose or hint what the message is, for that would be spoiling the entire experience. But it should be played, and it should be played to the end (which was somewhat over four hours for me). It's beautiful, it's potentially deeply disturbing, but it's brilliant.p.s. it's also very interresting to read some reviews about it (I suggest, even if that seems wrong, to read those AFTER you played it). There are some reviewers who ""get it"", and some that treat it purely for its game content, which is (minor spoiler alert) somewhat ironic.tl;dr: total recommendation"
