,Recommended,221260,16367278,"Posted: 13 June, 2015",all,Andy,"The only real objective is to set things on fire. The whole game is set in a single fixed camera view of a fireplace. You use coins to purchase a variety of objects to set on fire, and if you set specific items on fire at the same time, it counts as a combo which gives you a bonus. That process alone, buying each item and doing each combo, took about 5 hours for me to do. For such a simple premise, there's a lot of content to work with.It's not just a singular concept, though. There's an underlying plot. That too is a bit simple, but it's still very interesting. I find it might be more enjoyable to personally experience learning the plot, rather than read about it from someone else. And for me, there were two parts of plot development that I found somewhat disturbing/freaky/unsettling - which I find a positive attribute, because rarely can a game affect me on that level.Either way, it's just a fun way to spend time. I think it has replayability, because even after seeing all the objects set on fire, it's still cool to mess around with putting together multiple objects to see the outcome, but also simply because you get to set things on fire, so it's fun to just start it up for a quick session just for that sake."
